# Tier 5 (alpha premultiplication) baseline
# Date: 2026-04-23  |  Commit: fb92135  |  Hardware: AMD Ryzen 9 7950X
# Command: cargo bench --bench bench_t5_alpha
#
# Throughput at 4096px. Straight‚ÜíPremul (multiply) and Premul‚ÜíStraight
# (divide), across U8/U16/F32/F16 √ó 2ch (GrayA) and 4ch (RGBA):
#
#                              Straight‚ÜíPremul       Premul‚ÜíStraight
#   GrayA U8                    170.25 GiB/s            7.55 GiB/s
#   GrayA U16                    80.37                  6.43
#   GrayA F32                    33.52                 10.77
#   GrayA F16                     2.20                  2.19
#   RGBA U8                      23.01                  3.15
#   RGBA U16                     22.24                  2.17
#   RGBA F32                     13.74                  7.51
#   RGBA F16                      0.99                  0.94     ‚Üê worst
#
# Findings:
#
# 1. **F16 floor: all 4 F16 paths cluster around 1-2 GiB/s**, regardless of
#    direction or layout. Same root cause as T2: scalar f16_bits_to_f32 /
#    f32_to_f16_bits per lane. F16C SIMD should lift these 10-15√ó.
#
# 2. **Asymmetry: premul cheaper than unpremul.** Multiply is 1 cycle, divide
#    is 15-20 cycles on x86. Visible in every type: Straight‚ÜíPremul is 2-10√ó
#    faster than Premul‚ÜíStraight in the same row.
#
# 3. **GrayA U8 Straight‚ÜíPremul at 170 GiB/s** ‚Äî essentially at memory
#    bandwidth. Tight loop: (v * a + 128) / 255 per pixel, autovectorized
#    perfectly for 2-channel u8.
#
# 4. **RGBA U16 and F32 2ch paths** come in at 22-33 GiB/s ‚Äî the per-type
#    autoversion refactor paid off here. RGBA F32 Straight‚ÜíPremul at 13.7
#    GiB/s uses garb's SIMD path.
#
# 5. Premul‚ÜíStraight paths are consistently ~3√ó slower than their Straight‚Üí
#    Premul counterparts except for F32 RGBA (2√ó ‚Äî garb has a tuned unpremul
#    variant) and F16 (no gap because f16 conversion dominates the cost).
#
# Action items:
#   - F16 SIMD is the same fix here as in T2. 10-15√ó expected.
#   - The U16 Premul‚ÜíStraight at 2.17 GiB/s is the next-slowest non-F16
#    case. Our autoversion kernel does `(v * 65535 + a/2) / a` ‚Äî the
#    divide-per-lane is the bottleneck. SIMD integer divide is expensive;
#    could use reciprocal estimate + Newton refinement, or LUT for small
#    alpha.
